2022-07-12

Estimations (Part A)

The general model for estimation is as follows:

\[\begin{align*} \text{ln } p_{ijk} &= \alpha + \beta sim_{ij} + \gamma_1 \rho_k + \gamma_2 \theta_{ij} + \gamma_3 tariff_{ijk} \\ & + \gamma_4 NTM_{ijk}^{Tech} + \gamma_5 NTM_{ijk}^{Non-Tech} + \gamma_{6i}(NTM_{ijk}^{Tech} \times \delta_i) + \gamma_{7i}(NTM_{ijk}^{Non-Tech} \times \delta_i) \\ & + \gamma_8 DIG_i + \epsilon_{ijk} \end{align*}\]

where

\(DIG_i\) is the average score of separate Pillar measures capturing digital-trade regulation imposed by country \(i\) on all imports
\(\rho\) is the HS6 product fixed effects dummy variable (since regressions are estimated at chapter-level (i.e.there are 96 separate regressions)
\(\theta\) is the pair characteristics (i.e.distance, contiguity, landlocked status, common language, and RTA)
\(tariff_{ijk}\) is the applied tariff (MFN or lowest preferential, if available) imposed by \(i\) on imports of product \(k\) from \(j\)
\(NTM_{ijk}^{Tech}\) is the count of separate non-tariff measures from chapters A to C imposed by \(i\) on imports of product \(k\) from \(j\)
\(NTM_{ijk}^{Non-Tech}\) is the count of separate non-tariff measures from chapters D to O imposed by \(i\) on imports of product \(k\) from \(j\)
\(sim_{ij}\) is a measure of regulatory similarity of country \(i\) and \(j\)
\(\delta_{i}\) is fixed effect of country \(i\) (included for interaction with \(NTM\))

Model 1

\[\begin{align*} \text{ln } p_{ijk} &= \alpha + \beta sim_{ij} + \gamma_1 \rho_k + \epsilon_{ijk} \end{align*}\]

library(dplyr)

dta.df <- as.data.frame(cbind(HS_2, results.A, results.B))
colnames(dta.df) <- c('HS2','n','Adj-R2', 'b_regsim', 'p')

dta.df$bRegsim <- with(dta.df, ifelse(p > 0.1, 0, b_regsim))
dta.df_ <- as.data.frame(sapply(dta.df, as.numeric))

head(select(dta.df, -b_regsim))                 # head(dta.df)

## 6  06  849 0.512208412429365 0.0832446586510528 -0.853658835785104
regsim_sig.M1 <- nrow(dta.df_[dta.df_$bRegsim!=0,])
regsim_sig.POS.M1 <- nrow(dta.df_[dta.df_$bRegsim>0,])

Adj_R.avg.M1 <- mean(dta.df_[['Adj-R2']])

When considering 96-sectors (at the HS-2 level), we find only 11 digital measure coefficients (of which 0 are positive and 11 are negative) to be significant at the 10 percent level, and the average Adjusted R-square of the regressions is 0.3496806 .

aves.dta <- read.csv(paste0(path_, "aves_", model, ".csv"))

mean(aves.dta$aves_regsim, na.rm=TRUE)

## [1] -1.917133
mean(aves.dta$aves_regsimNPos, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] -0.7138406
print(AVES_mean_NPos.M1 <- weighted.mean(aves.dta$aves_regsimNPos, aves.dta$tradevalue, na.rm = TRUE))
## [1] -1.026391
hist(aves.dta$NPos)

The average weighted (by trade value) is -1.9171326 (and -1.0263908 when considering non-positive AVEs) Further note that the fraction of negative AVES is 0.0480264 ; zero AVES is 0.9519736 and positive AVES is 0.
